description:
## Problem
Worktrees reinstall npm packages on every launch even though we symlink .pi/npm/.

Root cause: launchWorktreeSession() checks !existsSync(worktreePiNpmDir) before creating symlink.
But bd worktree create already copied .pi/ directory, so the check fails and symlink is skipped.

## Fix
Replace the conditional symlink with force-replace logic:
1. Remove existing .pi/npm/ in worktree (if not already correct symlink)
2. Create symlink to main repo's .pi/npm/

## Code Change
cli/src/utils/worktree-session.ts lines 175-183:

Before:
```typescript
if (existsSync(projectPiNpmDir) && !existsSync(worktreePiNpmDir)) {
    try { symlinkSync(projectPiNpmDir, worktreePiNpmDir); } catch { /* non-fatal */ }
}
```

After:
```typescript
// Always ensure symlink to main repo's .pi/npm/ (shared cache)
if (existsSync(projectPiNpmDir)) {
    try {
        const existing = lstatSync(worktreePiNpmDir, { throwIfNoEntry: false });
        if (existing) {
            if (existing.isSymbolicLink() && readlinkSync(worktreePiNpmDir) === projectPiNpmDir) {
                // Already correct symlink
            } else {
                rmSync(worktreePiNpmDir, { recursive: true, force: true });
                symlinkSync(projectPiNpmDir, worktreePiNpmDir);
            }
        } else {
            symlinkSync(projectPiNpmDir, worktreePiNpmDir);
        }
    } catch { /* non-fatal */ }
}
```

## Context

pi-dex hooks the 'input' event to prepend '› ' to every user message before display, and hooks the 'context' event to strip that prefix back before the message reaches the model. This gives a visual cue in the TUI that a message is user-authored, while keeping the model context clean.

xtrm-ui has no input or context event handlers — messages have no prefix.

## What to build

Add two event handlers inside the xtrmUiExtension function (after registerCommands, before session_start):

**input handler:**
```ts
pi.on("input", async (event) => {
  if (event.source === "extension") return { action: "continue" };
  if (!event.text.trim()) return { action: "continue" };
  if (event.text.startsWith("/") || event.text.startsWith("!")) return { action: "continue" };
  if (event.text.startsWith("› ")) return { action: "continue" };
  return event.images
    ? { action: "transform", text: `› ${event.text}`, images: event.images }
    : { action: "transform", text: `› ${event.text}` };
});
```

**context handler:**
```ts
pi.on("context", async (event) => {
  const messages = event.messages.map((message) => {
    if (message.role === "user" && typeof message.content === "string" && message.content.startsWith("› "))
      return { ...message, content: message.content.slice(2) };
    if (message.role === "user" && Array.isArray(message.content)) {
      return {
        ...message,
        content: message.content.map((item, index) =>
          index === 0 && item.type === "text" && item.text.startsWith("› ")
            ? { ...item, text: item.text.slice(2) }
            : item
        ),
      };
    }
    return message;
  });
  return { messages };
});
```

## Acceptance criteria

- [ ] User input in the TUI shows '› ' prefix visually
- [ ] Commands (/xtrm-ui-*) and shell escapes (!) are NOT prefixed
- [ ] Messages sent to the model do NOT contain '› ' prefix
- [ ] Multipart (image) messages are handled: prefix added to text, images preserved
- [ ] Extension compiles

## Approach notes

- Reference: /tmp/package/src/index.ts → pi.on("input") and pi.on("context") handlers (lines ~170-205)
- The handlers are copied almost verbatim — only cosmetic renaming needed
- Gotcha: the '› ' is TWO chars (› = U+203A + space). Copy character directly from pi-dex source, do not approximate with >
- Place handlers between registerCommands() call and the session_start handler

## Layer

Boundary layer — transforms event data flowing between Pi runtime and model context.

## Context
Beads gate hooks require beads (bd CLI) and dolt (SQL server). xtrm must own this installation independently — users may use xtrm without specialists. The install logic is straightforward and can be copied directly from the specialists installer.

## What beads+dolt are (explain to user during install)
Beads is a git-backed issue tracker (bd CLI) that the xtrm workflow hooks use to enforce session-scoped work tracking. Dolt is the SQL+git backend that beads uses for persistent storage. Without them the workflow hooks install but provide zero enforcement (they fail open silently).

These are optional but strongly recommended — install them to get the full workflow enforcement experience.

## Install logic to implement (mirror specialists exactly)

### beads
```js
if (isInstalled('bd')) {
  skip('bd already installed');
} else {
  info('Installing @beads/bd...');
  npmInstallGlobal('@beads/bd');
  ok('bd installed');
}
```

### dolt
```js
function installDolt() {
  if (process.platform === 'darwin') {
    spawnSync('brew', ['install', 'dolt'], { stdio: 'inherit' });
  } else {
    spawnSync('sudo', ['bash', '-c',
      'curl -L https://github.com/dolthub/dolt/releases/latest/download/install.sh | bash'
    ], { stdio: 'inherit' });
  }
}
if (isInstalled('dolt')) {
  skip('dolt already installed');
} else {
  installDolt();
}
```

## Install flow in xtrm install all
1. Show section: 'beads + dolt (workflow enforcement backend)'
2. Print one-line explanation of what they are and why
3. Check if already installed (isInstalled('bd') + isInstalled('dolt'))
4. If present: skip with ok message, proceed to install beads hooks
5. If absent: prompt 'Install beads + dolt? Required for workflow enforcement hooks [Y/n]'
   - Yes (or --yes flag): run install, then install beads hooks
   - No: skip beads hooks, print note that they can be installed later with xtrm install all
6. In --yes mode: auto-installs beads+dolt without prompting (safe for CI/automation)

## Key difference from specialists
- xtrm installs hooks to ~/.claude/hooks/ (user-global, HOME-relative, not CWD-relative)
- specialists installs to CWD/.claude/hooks/ (project-scoped)
- xtrm must use: join(homedir(), '.claude', 'hooks') NOT join(process.cwd(), '.claude', 'hooks')

## Acceptance criteria
- isInstalled('bd') check works correctly
- isInstalled('dolt') check works correctly
- Install logic mirrors specialists bin/install.js exactly (same npm package, same dolt curl)
- User sees clear explanation of what beads+dolt are before being prompted
- --yes auto-installs without prompting
- Beads hooks only installed after deps confirmed present
- xtrm install basic skips this entire section (no beads dep check, no beads hooks)

## Open idea review
Should xtrm check beads health (bd doctor) after install rather than just checking the binary exists? A present binary with a broken db or misconfigured project could silently fail. Consider whether a post-install bd doctor run is worth the extra latency and noise in the install output.

